XPS analysis is an effective technique for analyzing the elemental properties of prepared materials. The salient features of GO and NGOs and the effect of nitrogen doping were studied using XPS. The wide- scan of GO is shown in Fig. 8(a). The distinctive peaks of C1s (∼285 eV) and O1s (∼531 eV) can be seen. The survey spectrum of NGO2 and NGO3 is shown in Fig. 8(b). The peak around 400 eV corresponds to N1s, and it confirms the presence of nitrogen in the NGOs. The two more distinctive peaks for C1s (∼284 eV) and O1s (∼531 eV) are clearly visible for carbon and oxygen, respectively. No impurity peaks were present in the sample. The atomic percentages of nitrogen are found to be 4.07 %, 5.16 %, and 6.64 % in the samples NGO1, NGO2, and NGO3, respectively (Table 4
                        ). Fig. 9
                         shows the nitrogen-doped graphene oxide structure with pyrrolic, pyridinic, and graphitic nitrogen incorporation.
